According to the always-sobering Living Wage Calculator, which attempts to quantify the real cost of existence, the [living wage](/Living_wage) for the city of Montgomery is estimated at US$19.73 per hour, or approximately $41,038 per year, for a single individual. For a family of four, the figure dramatically increases to $37.14 per hour, translating to a rather daunting $77,251 per year &#91;65&#93;. These figures, while perhaps disheartening, are notably slightly lower than the state averages for Alabama, which stand at $20.15 per hour for an individual and $41.11 for a family of four &#91;66&#93;. It's a stark contrast to the state's minimum wage, which stubbornly remains at a mere US$7.25 per hour &#91;67&#93;, highlighting a significant gap between what is legally mandated and what is actually required for a basic, dignified standard of living.

## Health care

Montgomery serves as a critical hub for healthcare services, not just for its immediate residents but for the broader central Alabama and [Black Belt](/Black_Belt_(region_of_Alabama)) region. This regional importance means that the city's medical facilities are often stretched to serve a wider population, a testament to their established expertise and infrastructure. Key hospitals located within the city include Baptist Medical Center South, strategically positioned on South East Boulevard, and Baptist Medical Center East, found adjacent to the sprawling campus of [Auburn University Montgomery](/Auburn_University_Montgomery) on Taylor Road. Additionally, Jackson Hospital, a significant healthcare provider, is conveniently located next to Oak Park, just off [Interstate 85](/Interstate_85).

Beyond providing direct patient care, Montgomery is also home to two burgeoning medical school campuses, fostering the next generation of healthcare professionals. Baptist Medical Center South hosts a branch of the esteemed [University of Alabama at Birmingham](/University_of_Alabama_at_Birmingham) medical school, integrating academic rigor with clinical practice. Similarly, Jackson Hospital operates a campus affiliated with the Alabama Medical Education Consortium, further enhancing the city's role in medical education and research. These institutions not only contribute to the local economy but also ensure a pipeline of skilled medical talent for the region, though one might argue the demand still outstrips the supply.

## Law and government

•
See also: [List of mayors of Montgomery, Alabama](/List_of_mayors_of_Montgomery,_Alabama) and [Montgomery Police Department (Alabama)](/Montgomery_Police_Department_(Alabama))

Montgomery operates under a conventional [Mayor–council government](/Mayor%E2%80%93council_government) system, a structure designed, in theory, to balance executive and legislative powers. Both the mayor and the nine council members are elected to four-year terms, providing a modicum of stability, or at least predictability, to the political landscape. The current mayor is [Steven Reed](/Steven_Reed_(mayor)) &#91;68&#93;, whose election on October 8, 2019, in a runoff, marked a significant historical milestone as he became the city's first African-American mayor &#91;69&#93;. This achievement, while celebrated, also serves as a stark reminder of how long it took for such representation to be realized. The city council, comprising nine members, is elected from nine distinct single-member districts, each theoretically representing an equal population slice, ensuring local voices, however disparate, are present in governance.

As the designated [seat](/County_seat) of [Montgomery County](/Montgomery_County,_Alabama), the city is the inevitable location for county courts and the county commission, whose members are elected separately, creating another layer of administrative complexity. Beyond its local and county functions, Montgomery proudly, or perhaps wearily, serves as the capital of Alabama, and as such, it hosts a myriad of essential [state government](/Government_of_Alabama) offices. These include the office of the [Governor](/Governor_of_Alabama), the bicameral [Alabama Legislature](/Alabama_Legislature), and the esteemed [Alabama Supreme Court](/Alabama_Supreme_Court), all of which contribute to the city's substantial governmental workforce and its undeniable political gravity within the state.

At the federal level, Montgomery's diverse population and geographic sprawl mean it is carved into portions of Alabama's [2nd](/Alabama%27s_2nd_congressional_district), [7th](/Alabama%27s_7th_congressional_district), and [3rd Congressional district](/Alabama%27s_3rd_congressional_district). These districts are currently represented by [Barry Moore](/Barry_Moore_(American_politician)), [Terri Sewell](/Terri_Sewell), and [Mike Rogers](/Mike_D._Rogers), respectively, each navigating the complexities of their diverse constituents. The 7th Congressional District encompasses most of Western Montgomery, reflecting a more urban and often historically African-American voting bloc. The 2nd District covers both Southern and Northern Montgomery, a blend of suburban and rural areas. Finally, the 3rd Congressional District extends into Eastern Montgomery, typically representing more affluent and rapidly developing suburban communities. This intricate partitioning ensures that Montgomery's varied interests are, at least theoretically, voiced in the halls of Congress.

