According to the [Uniform Crime Report](/Uniform_Crime_Report) (UCR) statistics, a standardized collection of data compiled by the [Federal Bureau of Investigation](/Federal_Bureau_of_Investigation) (FBI), Montgomery's crime landscape in 2022 presented a somewhat troubling picture. The city recorded 522 violent crimes and 2,636 property crimes per 100,000 residents. Breaking down these figures, the violent crimes included 18 murders, 9 forcible rapes, 141 robberies, and a significant 354 aggravated assaults. Property offenses, which often reflect economic distress, were characterized by 562 burglaries, 1,773 larceny-thefts, 301 motor vehicle thefts, and, thankfully, 0 reported acts of arson. These numbers, while just statistics, represent very real impacts on the lives of residents.

More recent data indicates a concerning trend in homicides. According to the city's own reporting, there were 75 homicides in 2023 &#91;70&#93;, a stark increase from the 18 reported per 100,000 residents in the 2020 UCR, even accounting for population changes.

When compared to other major cities within Alabama, Montgomery's violent crime rates unfortunately stack up unfavorably, a reality that often sparks considerable local debate and concern. While in 2009, Montgomery's crime rates were considered relatively favorable when juxtaposed against other large Alabamian cities such as [Huntsville](/Huntsville,_Alabama), [Mobile](/Mobile,_Alabama), and [Birmingham](/Birmingham,_Alabama), this trend reversed sharply in the 2010s and early 2020s. This period saw a distressing surge in criminal activity, culminating in a record high of over 320 shooting victims and more than 77 homicide victims in 2021 alone &#91;71&#93; &#91;72&#93;. By 2022, Montgomery's violent crime rate stood at 514 per 100,000, earning it a rather dismal crime score rating of only 9/100, a clear indicator of persistent challenges &#91;73&#93;. For property crimes, Montgomery's average is generally comparable to Alabama's other large cities, suggesting a widespread issue, but it remains noticeably higher than both the overall state and national averages, indicating that residents, sadly, need to be extra vigilant about their belongings.

## Recreation

Montgomery, for all its historical weight, does manage to offer a surprising amount of recreational reprieve. The city boasts an impressive expanse of over 1,600 acres of parkland, meticulously maintained and operated by the City of Montgomery Parks and Recreation Department. One might almost believe they care about public well-being. This department, in its tireless efforts, also oversees the operation of 24 community centers, providing vital local hubs for various activities and gatherings. For the more adventurous, a dedicated skate park offers a designated space for wheeled acrobatics. Golf enthusiasts have their choice of two courses, Lagoon Park and Gateway Park, to test their patience and swing. The venerable Cramton Bowl Stadium and Multiplex serves as a central venue for a range of sporting events and public gatherings. Two tennis centers, Lagoon Park and O'Conner, cater to the racket-wielding populace. Meanwhile, families can find solace in 65 playgrounds, while aspiring athletes can hone their skills on 90 baseball/softball fields and 24 soccer fields, including the modern [Emory Folmar](/Emory_Folmar) Soccer Facility. And, for a touch of old-world charm, the department even operates a riverboat, offering scenic cruises along the Alabama River, a gentle reminder of the city's historical connection to its waterways &#91;74&#93;.

## Culture

Montgomery, perhaps surprisingly for a city of its size, cultivates one of the most vibrant and extensive arts scenes in mid-sized America. It's almost as if they understand that life isn't *just* about industry and politics. The Winton M. Blount Cultural Park, named for the late [Winton M. Blount](/Winton_M._Blount), is an expansive haven in east Montgomery dedicated to cultural enrichment. Within its serene grounds resides the distinguished [Montgomery Museum of Fine Arts](/Montgomery_Museum_of_Fine_Arts), whose permanent collections offer a compelling narrative through American art and sculpture, a focused exploration of [Southern](/Southern_United_States) art, master prints from European masters, and exquisite collections of porcelain and glass works &#91;75&#93;. Complementing this, the Society of Arts and Crafts maintains a cooperative gallery, providing a vital platform for local artists to showcase their talents and contribute to the city's creative pulse &#91;76&#93;.

For those with a penchant for the wilder side of existence, the [Montgomery Zoo](/Montgomery_Zoo) offers a global safari, housing over 500 animals representing five continents, all within 40 acres (0.16&#160;km 2 ) of thoughtfully designed, barrier-free habitats &#91;77&#93;. History buffs and country music aficionados can immerse themselves in the legacy of a true icon at the Hank Williams Museum, which proudly displays one of the largest collections of Williams memorabilia anywhere in the world &#91;78&#93;. The official state history museum, the Museum of Alabama, is conveniently located within the [Alabama Department of Archives and History](/Alabama_Department_of_Archives_and_History) building downtown. This institution, a repository of the state's collective memory, underwent a substantial $10 million renovation and expansion in 2013, incorporating technological upgrades and numerous new exhibits and displays, ensuring its continued relevance and accessibility &#91;79&#93;. For a glimpse into the cosmos, the [W. A. Gayle Planetarium](/W._A._Gayle_Planetarium), operated by [Troy University](/Troy_University), stands as one of the largest in the southeastern United States. It offers captivating tours of the night sky and engaging shows that delve into current topics in [astronomy](/Astronomy). The planetarium itself received a significant upgrade in 2014, transitioning to a full-dome digital projector, enhancing the immersive experience for visitors &#91;80&#93;, proving that even the stars need a technological facelift sometimes.

The Blount Cultural Park is also home to the impressive Carolyn Blount Theatre, the main stage for the [Alabama Shakespeare Festival](/Alabama_Shakespeare_Festival). The Shakespeare Festival offers a year-round schedule of performances, encompassing both timeless classic plays and productions of local interest, alongside the essential works of [William Shakespeare](/William_Shakespeare) himself &#91;81&#93;, ensuring a constant stream of dramatic engagement. The 1200-seat Davis Theatre for the Performing Arts, nestled on the [Troy University at Montgomery](/Troy_University_at_Montgomery) campus, first opened its doors in 1930 and underwent a significant renovation in 1983. It serves as the esteemed home for the [Montgomery Symphony Orchestra](/Montgomery_Symphony_Orchestra), the Alabama Dance Theatre, and the Montgomery Ballet, in addition to hosting a variety of other theatrical productions &#91;82&#93;. The Symphony, a cornerstone of the city's classical music scene, has been performing in Montgomery since 1979 &#91;83&#93;. For those with a taste for the unconventional, the Capri Theatre in [Cloverdale](/Cloverdale,_Montgomery), originally built in 1941, has carved out a niche for itself, dedicating its screens today to showcasing [independent films](/Independent_film) &#91;84&#93;, a refreshing alternative to mainstream fare. Further enhancing the city's performing arts offerings, the 1800-seat, state-of-the-art Montgomery Performing Arts Center opened its doors in 2007, integrated within the newly renovated convention center downtown. This versatile venue hosts a broad spectrum of performances, from touring Broadway plays to concerts featuring legendary artists such as [B. B. King](/B._B._King), [Gregg Allman](/Gregg_Allman), and [Merle Haggard](/Merle_Haggard), solidifying Montgomery's place on the national touring circuit.

Montgomery has, over the years, served as the fertile ground for numerous musical performers who have achieved national and international recognition. These include Toni Tennille, half of the popular duo The Captain and Tennille; the iconic jazz singer and pianist [Nat King Cole](/Nat_King_Cole), whose smooth voice transcended genres; the legendary country singer [Hank Williams](/Hank_Williams), whose raw talent and tragic life left an indelible mark on American music &#91;85&#93;; the powerful blues singer [Big Mama Thornton](/Big_Mama_Thornton); [Melvin Franklin](/Melvin_Franklin) of the legendary vocal group [The Temptations](/The_Temptations); and the accomplished guitarist [Tommy Shaw](/Tommy_Shaw) of the classic rock band [Styx](/Styx_(band)) &#91;86&#93;.

The city also boasts literary and artistic connections. Author and artist [Zelda Sayre](/Zelda_Sayre), a formidable talent in her own right and the future wife of F. Scott Fitzgerald, was born in Montgomery. It was here, in 1918, that she first encountered [F. Scott Fitzgerald](/F._Scott_Fitzgerald), then a young soldier stationed at a nearby Army post, setting in motion one of the most iconic and tumultuous literary romances of the 20th century. The house where they lived during the initial, heady phase of their marriage is now lovingly preserved and operated as the F. Scott and Zelda Fitzgerald Museum &#91;87&#93; &#91;88&#93;, offering a glimpse into their complicated lives. The esteemed poet [Sidney Lanier](/Sidney_Lanier) also made his home in Montgomery and nearby [Prattville](/Prattville,_Alabama) immediately following the [American Civil War](/American_Civil_War), a period during which he penned his novel *Tiger Lilies* &#91;89&#93;, further cementing the region's literary ties.

In addition to these notable earlier musicians, some rock bands originating from Montgomery have achieved national success since the late 20th century, proving that creativity isn't bound by genre or era. Local artists [Trust Company](/Trust_Company_(band)) famously secured a record deal with [Geffen Records](/Geffen_Records) in 2002, bringing their sound to a wider audience. Similarly, [Hot Rod Circuit](/Hot_Rod_Circuit) formed in Montgomery in 1997 under the earlier moniker Antidote, but found greater acclaim with [Vagrant Records](/Vagrant_Records) after strategically relocating to [Connecticut](/Connecticut), demonstrating that sometimes, even talent needs a change of scenery.

## Sports

Montgomery, ever eager to assert its identity, is the proud home of the [Montgomery Biscuits](/Montgomery_Biscuits) baseball team, a Class AA affiliate of the [Tampa Bay Rays](/Tampa_Bay_Rays) within the [Southern League](/Southern_League_(1964%E2%80%932020)). They play their games at the rather charming [Montgomery Riverwalk Stadium](/Montgomery_Riverwalk_Stadium), a venue that has seen its fair share of diamond action. Riverwalk Stadium notably hosted the [NCAA Division II](/NCAA_Division_II) National Baseball Championship from 2004 until 2007, a mantle previously held by [Paterson Field](/Paterson_Field), another Montgomery staple, from 1985 until 2003 &#91;90&#93;. The stadium has also been chosen to host two Southern League All-Star games, in 2006 and again in 2015, celebrating the region's passion for America's pastime.

Beyond baseball, the [Yokohama Tire LPGA Classic](/Yokohama_Tire_LPGA_Classic), a prominent women's golf event, graces the immaculate greens of the [Robert Trent Jones Golf Trail](/Robert_Trent_Jones_Golf_Trail) at Capitol Hill in nearby [Prattville](/Prattville,_Alabama) &#91;91&#93;, attracting top talent to the area. [Garrett Coliseum](/Garrett_Coliseum) once served as the home turf for the now-defunct [Montgomery Bears](/Montgomery_Bears) [indoor football](/Indoor_American_football) team, a fleeting venture into a more aggressive form of sport.

Montgomery is also a significant locus for collegiate sporting events, driven by its array of colleges and universities. The [Alabama State University](/Alabama_State_University) Hornets compete fiercely in [NCAA Division I](/NCAA_Division_I) within the [Southwestern Athletic Conference](/Southwestern_Athletic_Conference) (SWAC). Their [football](/American_football) team charges onto the field at Hornet Stadium, while the basketball teams showcase their skills at the Dunn-Oliver Acadome. The baseball team, meanwhile, enjoys the modern amenities of the ASU Baseball Complex, which officially opened its gates in 2010. [Auburn University at Montgomery](/Auburn_University_at_Montgomery) (AUM) fields competitive teams in [NCAA Division II](/NCAA_Division_II) competition, adding another layer of athletic prowess to the city. [Huntingdon College](/Huntingdon_College) participates at the NCAA Division III level, proving that competitive spirit isn't solely reserved for the largest institutions, and [Faulkner University](/Faulkner_University), a member of the NAIA, maintains a spirited rivalry with AUM, keeping local fans engaged.

Historically, Montgomery was the long-standing host of the [Blue–Gray Football Classic](/Blue%E2%80%93Gray_Football_Classic), an annual college football [all-star game](/All-star_game) that ran from 1938 until 2001 &#91;92&#93;, a tradition fondly remembered by many. In 2009, the city proudly hosted the inaugural annual Historical Black College and University (HBCU) All-Star Football Bowl, played at Cramton Bowl, a significant event celebrating the rich athletic heritage of these institutions. Montgomery has also been the setting for the [Southern Intercollegiate Athletic Conference](/Southern_Intercollegiate_Athletic_Conference) (SIAC) football championship and the increasingly popular [Camellia Bowl](/Camellia_Bowl_(2014%E2%80%93present)) &#91;93&#93;, further solidifying its reputation as a sports destination. Annually, Montgomery plays host to the Max Capital City Classic within Riverwalk Stadium, a highly anticipated baseball showdown between fierce rivals [Auburn University](/Auburn_University) and the [University of Alabama](/University_of_Alabama), a contest that always draws a passionate crowd.

Beyond the local teams, several highly successful professional athletes hail from Montgomery, leaving their mark on national and international stages. These include [Pro Football Hall of Famer](/Pro_Football_Hall_of_Fame) [Bart Starr](/Bart_Starr) &#91;94&#93;, whose legendary career with the Green Bay Packers is etched in football history, and [Alonzo Babers](/Alonzo_Babers) &#91;95&#93;, a [two-time Olympic gold medalist](/Athletics_at_the_1984_Summer_Olympics) in track and field, whose speed brought glory to both himself and his hometown.

## Civic organizations

Montgomery benefits from a dense network of active governmental and nonprofit civic organizations, each striving to improve the city in its own way. Among the city-funded initiatives is the Montgomery Clean City Commission, an affiliate of the national Keep America Beautiful program, which tirelessly works to promote cleanliness and environmental awareness. Then there's BONDS (Building Our Neighborhoods for Development and Success), an organization dedicated to engaging citizens with city and nonprofit programs, coordinating and assisting neighborhood associations, and striving to instill a sense of neighborhood and civic pride among Montgomery residents. It's a noble effort, even if the results are often debated.

A significant number of organizations are, quite rightly, focused on diversity relations and preserving the city's rich, and often painful, [civil rights](/Civil_rights) history. Leadership Montgomery provides crucial citizenship training, aiming to cultivate informed and engaged community leaders. Bridge Builders Alabama works with high school youth to promote diversity and civic engagement, perhaps hoping to instill some wisdom before cynicism sets in. The group [One Montgomery](/One_Montgomery), founded in 1983, serves as an important forum for networking among a diverse group of citizens actively involved in civic affairs, fostering dialogue where it's desperately needed. Montgomery is also home to a constellation of powerful institutions dedicated to remembering and educating about this critical period: [The Legacy Museum](/The_Legacy_Museum), the solemn [Civil Rights Memorial](/Civil_Rights_Memorial), the profoundly impactful [The National Memorial for Peace and Justice](/The_National_Memorial_for_Peace_and_Justice), the evolving [Freedom Monument Sculpture Park](/Freedom_Monument_Sculpture_Park), the [Freedom Rides Museum](/Freedom_Rides_Museum), the National Center for the Study of Civil Rights and African-American Culture, and the essential [Rosa Parks Library and Museum](/Rosa_Parks_Museum) &#91;96&#93;. These institutions collectively ensure that the lessons of the past are not, or at least should not be, forgotten.

## Education

The vast majority of the city of Montgomery and its surrounding county are served by the comprehensive [Montgomery Public Schools](/Montgomery_Public_Schools) system. As of 2022, this extensive system enrolled 26,381 students and employed 1,412 dedicated teachers, a considerable undertaking in public education &#91;98&#93;. The system manages a substantial portfolio of educational institutions, including 32 elementary schools, 13 middle schools, and 10 high schools. In addition to these traditional structures, it also oversees 6 highly specialized [magnet schools](/Magnet_school), 1 [alternative school](/Alternative_school) designed for diverse learning needs, and 2 [special education](/Special_education) centers, striving to cater to a broad spectrum of student requirements. Montgomery is notably one of the few cities in Alabama to host three public schools offering the rigorous [International Baccalaureate](/International_Baccalaureate) (IB) programs, a testament to its commitment to advanced academic curricula. In a nod to educational excellence, Forest Avenue Academic Magnet Elementary School was recognized as a [National Blue Ribbon School](/National_Blue_Ribbon_School) in 2007, with Bear Exploration Center receiving the same prestigious honor in 2015 &#91;99&#93;. Further cementing its academic reputation, [LAMP High School](/Loveless_Academic_Magnet_Program_(LAMP)) was lauded in 2022 by [U.S. News & World Report](/U.S._News_%26_World_Report) as the No. 7 [magnet school](/Magnet_school) in the entire United States and the No. 1 public high school in the state of Alabama &#91;100&#93;. Impressively, three other Montgomery Public Schools high schools—[Brewbaker Technology Magnet](/Brewbaker_Technology_Magnet_High_School) and [George Washington Carver High School](/George_Washington_Carver_High_School_(Montgomery,_Alabama))—also earned spots on this competitive list, marking the highest representation from any public school system in the state.

[Maxwell Air Force Base](/Maxwell_Air_Force_Base) residents benefit from a unique educational arrangement, with grades K-8 zoned to [Department of Defense Education Activity](/Department_of_Defense_Education_Activity) (DoDEA) schools &#91;97&#93;. The DoDEA directly operates Maxwell Air Force Base Elementary/Middle School, providing on-base education. For high school, Maxwell AFB residents are zoned to Montgomery Public Schools facilities: those residing on the main base attend Carver High, while those in the Gunner Annex are zoned to [Dr. Percy L. Julian High School](/Dr._Percy_L._Julian_High_School). Crucially, residents retain the option to attend magnet schools, offering a pathway to specialized academic programs &#91;102&#93;.

Beyond the public system, Montgomery is home to 28 private schools &#91;103&#93;, a landscape that historically included notable (and often controversial) [segregation academies](/Segregation_academies) such as [Montgomery Academy (Alabama)](/Montgomery_Academy_(Alabama)), institutions that arose during the period of desegregation. The [Montgomery City-County Public Library](/Montgomery_City-County_Public_Library) system extends its reach across the city and county, operating eleven public libraries, serving as vital community resources for knowledge and literacy. The city also houses Alabama's oldest law library, the Supreme Court and State Law Library, established in a rather impressive 1828. Located within the Heflin-Torbert Judicial Building, this library boasts a rare book collection containing works printed as early as 1605, offering a tangible link to centuries of legal thought.

In the realm of higher education, Montgomery is a significant academic center. It has been the proud home of [Alabama State University](/Alabama_State_University), a distinguished [historically black university](/Historically_black_colleges_and_universities) (HBCU), since the Lincoln Normal University for Teachers relocated from [Marion](/Marion,_Alabama) in 1887. Today, ASU stands as the second largest HBCU in Alabama, enrolling nearly 5,000 students drawn from 42 U.S. states and 7 countries &#91;104&#93;, a testament to its enduring legacy and appeal. The public [Troy University](/Troy_University) maintains a robust campus in downtown Montgomery, serving a student population of 3,000. This campus is also home to the poignant [Rosa Parks](/Rosa_Parks) Library and Museum, a powerful educational and historical site. Another prominent public institution, [Auburn University at Montgomery](/Auburn_University_at_Montgomery) (AUM), with an enrollment of nearly 5,000 students primarily from the [Montgomery metropolitan area](/Montgomery_metropolitan_area), is situated in the eastern part of the city &#91;105&#93;. Furthermore, Montgomery's Baptist Medical Center South hosts a branch of the highly regarded [University of Alabama at Birmingham](/University_of_Alabama_at_Birmingham) medical school on its campus along the Eastern Boulevard, contributing to the region's medical training capacity.

Montgomery also hosts several private colleges, each with its unique character. [Faulkner University](/Faulkner_University), with an enrollment of 2,952 students in Fall 2023 &#91;106&#93;, is a [Church of Christ](/Church_of_Christ)-affiliated institution that houses the prestigious [Thomas Goode Jones School of Law](/Thomas_Goode_Jones_School_of_Law). [Huntingdon College](/Huntingdon_College), which currently serves approximately 1,100 students, maintains an affiliation with the [United Methodist Church](/United_Methodist_Church) &#91;107&#93;, imbuing its academic mission with a particular values framework. Rounding out the private institutions is [Amridge University](/Amridge_University), further diversifying the city's educational offerings. Additionally, several two-year colleges provide vocational and associate degree programs, including [H. Councill Trenholm State Technical College](/H._Councill_Trenholm_State_Technical_College) &#91;108&#93;, offering practical pathways to employment.

Finally, [Maxwell Air Force Base](/Maxwell_Air_Force_Base) holds a unique and crucial role as the headquarters for [Air University](/Air_University_(United_States)), the [United States Air Force](/United_States_Air_Force)'s premier center for professional military education. Branches of Air University based in Montgomery include the [Squadron Officer School](/Squadron_Officer_School), the [Air Command and Staff College](/Air_Command_and_Staff_College), the [Air War College](/Air_War_College), and the [Community College of the Air Force](/Community_College_of_the_Air_Force) &#91;109&#93;. These institutions are responsible for training and developing the intellectual and leadership capabilities of Air Force personnel from around the globe, making Montgomery a hub for military thought and strategy.

